rate in their descriptions, even though they are completely different. What=
 seems clear is that the elephant is the Internet.=E2=80=9D
No longer are there equal and opposite reactions to GameStop; two different=
 lenses through which to understand the conflict. There are an unlimited nu=
mber of lenses.
Unlimited choice, proliferated by the Internet, is why =E2=80=9Ceveryone ha=
s a story about what happened with GameStop, and why they are all true,=E2=
=80=9D Thompson writes. =E2=80=9CThe 2019 story was correct, but so was the=
 summer 2020 story, and the fall 2020 story, and the January 2021 story. No=
ne of those stories, though, existed in isolation: they built on the storie=
s that came before, duplicating and mutating them along the way.
Think about the most powerful movements this year: GameStop, Bitcoin, $DOGE=
, Free Britney Spears, QAnon. All decentralized, all vastly open to interpr=
etation, all offering an unlimited number of lenses.
Will there be a time when audiences don=E2=80=99t want to follow a celebrit=
y just for their advice=E2=80=94recipes from Martha Stewart or career plans=
 from Sheryl Sandberg? A time when we ask not for explicit instructions, bu=
t for a treasure map?
The Martha Stewart of tomorrow may not look like a single person. It may go=
 even farther than AI influencers [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEm=
KhTAQQE9jlpJRzSKLhuZfQzKUGn5M7BhbvH3H76KhqIIaeNSzusCc8qW2tBd0p7FcG6gI5x6gFM=
jo2CGP3inS0YEJLpFT3JFBDMjv45QBVu2DKvkAtB0meKuLT_FzgTEVaFFOMNZp4zSduJSuA9vrr=
uPGAQxsAvNw9eE8RAsKfiFfKQIKaill2xv21dBXjfM8Wx_3oues19amtfaCD6v_OSDoe4e9ltCw=
b4jIK4opwZxKQgXDsiWtAbAgsaHEOaCm08Riwics-CCoMbTheJ1pux-mIuz7BqCsYiomZR_nOn4=
veoXwGdRXx1rXI_pyjRC1CeAeC-WR-fEyzhAhV8lu1KUqJLLHuJeCk_75umpioscC8w5Vskv1Kv=
5D_wDnsows] like Lil Miquela. It may be a loose collective, a single idea w=
ith a million fragments, a trailhead with innumerable paths to wander. It w=
ill look less like a cookbook, and more like a choose your own adventure no=
vel.=20
I often think of this quote by Walter Kirn in Harpers Magazine [https://ema=
il.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEluxCAQRU_T7NoqyuBhwSKbXMNiKNsoNjiAu-WcPqR7EalUo=
76-6lldaInpUkfMhf2lqVwHqUDPvFEplNiZKU3eKd7h0EoxMqeE44McmM_TnIh27TdV0knsOM3m=
rS4-hpcCACVbFTdz37dAzqEgtCjMDCTt6MRMsyT79tWn8xQsKXpQumIgtqm1lCPf2o8bftZYdTo=
o5SampU462dU_qHYIfKgFuprKSven_9HJ3eN8_64b5hUCchA4cpQtjA1vDJGlEQxy5whNp7kFLm=
aQYpBoDN4E7As2-TS5aPvV2LizpEIsJiYflnr-WvVO2-tQv55q3c_gyzVR0GYj9wZS3lxfiKaFA=
qXK2026VJp87AH6UQrevwFUYq3sQYLoWHV2sarCv-kvmLOOPg] in an essay on QAnon:=C2=
=A0
The audience for internet narratives doesn=E2=80=99t want to read, it wants=
 to write. It doesn=E2=80=99t want answers provided, it wants to search for=
 them. It doesn=E2=80=99t want to sit and be amused, it wants to be sent on=
 a mission. It wants to do.
