 #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">said </a>of her years as a stockbrok=
er. &#8220;It was very aggressive, and the money you made was amazing. I wa=
s making about $135,000, which was a lot.&#8221; <em>(That&#8217;s $1.1 mil=
lion today)</em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Stewart was early to the professional class of=
 women in 1965. But by 1970, things exploded: &#8220;Between 1970 and 1980,=
 the labor force participation rates of women in the 25&#8211;34 and 35&#82=
11;44 age groups increased by 20.5 percentage points and 14.4 percentage po=
ints, respectively. No other labor force group <strong>has ever experienced=
 an increase in participation rates of this magnitude in one decade,&#8221;=
 </strong>according to the BLS.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It was a tectonic shift i=
n the labor force. It was also a tectonic shift in American culture. Workin=
g women became mainstream, no longer fringe radicals burning bras. What did=
 that mean? The economic implications of the 1980s became the cultural impl=
ications of the 1990s: Sex, marriage, dating, kids. Decades of draconian tr=
adition, gone. The guard rails were off. The rules of the game were suddenl=
y very unclear. </p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">&#8220;It was a time when we were supposed to =
be newly empowered,&#8221; <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxF=
kM1qwzAQhJ8mutWsZMmWDzr00tcw-tnEIrIUpHWD375qUigsM7DDMuznLeGt1NM8SiP2KyudDzQ=
Zny0hEVZ2NKxrDIZPQo9KLiwYGbhWmsW2XivibmMyVA9kj8Ol6C3Fkl8XAEKxzUg-KX31k56CHo=
OalQctPARurUZw87vXHiFi9mjwG-tZMrJkNqJHu4yfF_HV5_l8DvmkuGMbfNn7RgBfuoHqwmWXR=
mfC7rThRz0Stg9Xyn3YaE8sGgGCgxQLF2qEZeCDQ_S4gBM8BBRustwDl1dQUivhnLhI2G9iaIdr=
ZP39t5VVkwu5UmO-9fi-2R3TK-jfr933I0c6V8zWJQxvMPTm-0K13jBj7dzDaqlT5csMMC9K8j8=
QndyoZlAgJ9abQ-lX-b_0B_fDkCo" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: und=
erline;">writes the New York Times&#8217; Taffy Brodesser-Akner.</a> &#8220=
;We were &#8217;90s women. The battles had been fought; we owned property a=
nd voted. We worked and talked endlessly about things like balance. The wom=
en&#8217;s magazines encouraged us to take initiative, to ask the guy out. =
We were on the pill. Colleges were giving out condoms, not just to the men =
but to the women. There were so many mixed messages, and the women I knew w=
ere at war to maintain their independence but also still traditional enough=
 to think about the families they&#8217;d been engineered to want.&#8221;</=
p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 1em 0;">In the late 1970s, after leaving Wall Street for the Connecticut=
 countryside, Martha must have felt the ground shifting. In those years, wh=
ile renovating her farmhouse, tilling the ground for vegetables, raising he=
r daughter, growing her catering business, applying the same ferocity to he=
r fruitcakes as she did her bond trades, Martha&#8217;s ambition never wane=
d. But a question arose: In all this ambition, who was being left behind?&n=
bsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 1em 0;">What about the women who still had to pack school lunches?=
 What about the women responsible for cooking Christmas dinner? What about =
Martha&#8217;s neighbors, the other mothers at school?&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Wa=
s anyone paying attention to them? Didn&#8217;t they have ambition too?</p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;">The job of full-time, professional homemaker &#8220;was flounderin=
g,&#8221; Martha <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OrCAQhZ=
-m2Y0pEFQWLGZzX8PwU22TVjCI1zhPP9W6mIRUVSiqDufztuKUy2nWvFX2CWM9VzQJj23GWrGwf=
cMyxmB4J4ZWSc2CkYEPamBxG58FcbFxNrXsyNbdzdHbGnO6JgCEYi_jfcuD956rZxi8tt2ggu37=
7qmE7HTvb127h4jJo8H_WM6ckM3mVeu6Pdrvh_hH5ziOhj525vLG0vi80N1iJ_sTE1IpAIASiE_=
NKVyLjrzY9EWPWTQCBAcpNBeqBd3wxiF61OAEDwGF6yz3wOUTlByUcE48JCyTaLbdbdX690eTFZ=
NydbnENFH7_bILzleD3I-Ulz3Feo6YrJsx3GDqzfdCNU6YsBD3MNpKVLnuAXqtJO9vEESuVT0ok=
B0j5UAGYvoT_QUwgZEU" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">=
said in an interview with Charlie Rose.</a> &#8220;We all wanted to escape =
it, to get out of the house, get that high-paying job and pay somebody else=
 to do everything that we didn&#8217;t think was really worthy of our atten=
tion. And all of a sudden I realized:<strong> it was terribly worthy of our=
 attention.</strong>&#8221;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Here&#8217;s some context from Nora=
 Ephron. &#8220;Lots of women didn&#8217;t feel like entering into the work=
force (or even sharing the raising of children with their husbands), but th=
ey felt guilty about this, so they were compelled to elevate full-time pare=
nthood to a sacrament.&#8221; </p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">A <em>sacrament.</em> That passi=
on, that need to prove value, to prove the worth of something underestimate=
d by the broader market, is exactly what Martha spotted. She identified not=
 just the trend, but the <em>countertrend. </em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1=
a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Mark Penn, the=
 author of &#8220;<a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkbtuwzAMR=
b8m2mzo6cegoUGQqZ2ydTH0YBIhtuRKcgz366vEQwGCBEhc3ItDozLcQtzkHFJGrzbkbQbpYU0j=
5AwRLQni4KwkDe2Y4D2yklvSiQ65NFwjwKTcKHNcAM2LHp1R2QX_VmBMBbpLy7umtbTpNGMds1j=
RnrZX6KwWjLegdl-1WAfegIQnxC14QKO85zynA_s40HOpdV1rNanf4GsTprL4ciaGHMHbVF1-Fh=
XBVucQDaTqFN3T-Vt1ciku8ytRqkCH8CgyO5d2xC3_vojv4ydykmJKMKc9oYLhvia1BjDQY02Jt=
UB1o4jBhF-x4J2gWtMDx9ON1mnRKSvzeOVBUfqQdYjFtpwfdzXB-D4ULEOZ0-Jd3gbwSo9gd2J5=
B_9mONzAQywPsYPKBTfpW4zbXnDS7oQKUiZaLDBvUHG2oaj8v-kfSV6a_w" style=3D"color:=
 #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Countertrends Squared</a>,&#8221; de=
fines the concept this way: &#8220;For every trend, there is a countertrend=
=2E It is human nature in the Informatio=
n Age: every move or desire in one di=
rection seems to inspire a countermovement by another group in the opposite=
 direction.&#8221;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">As information and choice proliferated, Amer=
ican culture began to no longer move in one direction at a time, but <em>tw=
o. </em>In the 1980s and 1990s, professional women were becoming an increas=
ingly powerful, important demographic. But in equal and opposite measure, h=
omemakers were important too. They had hopes. They had dreams. They had amb=
itions. And no one was paying attention.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">&#8220;It was about fi=
lling a void,&#8221; Stewart <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJ=
xFkE2LhDAMhn-NPUpaWz8OPSzsDMte97Qn6UdGy2grtY7477eOh4WQQEJ4eB-jEg4hHnIJayJn6=
9OxoPS4rxOmhJFsK8beWUlr1laCd8RKbmkrWuLW_hERZ-UmmeKGZNn05IxKLvj3BwATZJRGAG9b=
ZmxrGTcPLhjvsEYwoDSigYurNuvQG5T4wngEj2SSY0rLWlQfBbvn2ve9PMKWNo2lCfO5UcmMRXV=
_FdXnevt63X4A6u9f4iQDRoGzjjJRQVfS8iRhB5pRa5HpWlEDlD9A8FYwrVnBYR5YuW56Tco8Tw=
CJ0oekQ3R-yOfnqGac3occtM9z3rxLR49e6Qnt5SBdKt9W-gE9xqzY9iplgbRrAJpOcNpcmbOkS=
jSQ_dQkk23IX_4f-gd9i4oy" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underlin=
e;">said.</a> &#8220;Every time I wrote a book, it was to fill a void that =
I and my friends had to have filled. When I wrote a book about hors d'oeuvr=
es it was because there <em>wasn&#8217;t</em> a great book about hors d'oeu=
vres.&#8221;&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">How many categories&#8212;the hors d'oeuvres=
 of 2021&#8212;are we overlooking today by following the trends, but not th=
eir counters?</p><h3 style=3D"-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit=
